@node Requirements

GadMget requires an Amiga running Kickstart V37 (WorkBench 2.04) or higher
to operate.

GadMget opens the following libraries:

Library           Minimum Version #
-------           -----------------
graphics.library           37
utility.library            37
gadtools.library           37
asl.library                37
intuition.library          37
workbench.library          37   
icon.library		   33   (37 to use iconify)

@endnode

@node Output "GadMget Output format"

GadMget's output is meant to be pasted into the command line of your favorite 
ftp client.  

The output can be of two types:

The default variety ("Simple path output") is the one acceptable by most ftp 
clients.  It looks something like this:

-----BEGIN SAMPLE--------
cd biz/dbase
mget dfa-21.lha 
cd ../../comm/term
mget term-4.0-DVI.lha term-4.0-030.lha term-4.0-Doc.lha 
cd ../../dev/asm
mget BarflyDemo.lha memleak.lha 
cd ../../text/tex
mget mma2ltx.lha 
cd ../../util/app
mget AppMenu2_1.lha
-----END SAMPLE----------



If you are using ncftp, however, a more efficient form of output is available.
To generate this type of output, specify the NOSIMPLEPATHS parameter on the
command line or in the ToolTypes, or uncheck the "Use Simple Paths" menu
item.  This type of consists of nothing but "mget" commands, with the pathname
relative to Aminet's root directory prepended to each.  

-----BEGIN SAMPLE--------
mget util/misc/ReminderV11.lha docs/hyper/animeguide.lha util/cli/unxshell.lzh 
game/shoot/XenoDemo.lha util/cli/PushD37_1.lha game/think/Dozer.lha 
game/think/LittleGames.lha mus/edit/RGS-Util.lha mods/pro/Meaningless.lha
mods/pro/Cannon_Fodder.lha 
mget mods/misc/Memorydust.lha pix/trace/helmet.lha 
-----END SAMPLE----------

The output will go to the file specified in the @{"Output" link OutputArg} parameter, or
to stdout if there is no such parameter.  This alone won't do you much good, 
you need a @{"way to get enter it into your FTP program" link ServingSuggestion }.

@endnode


@node Introduction

Please read the @{"History" link History} section for information on changes 
and bug-fixes.

Being the incorrigible file-leeching weasel that I am, I like to download the
RECENT file off of Aminet and browse through it, "mget"ing anything and 
everything that catches my eye.  The only problem with this is that I have to 
type the name and directory of every file I want to download.

The extra thirty seconds a day this was costing me was simply intolerable, 
so I spent a few hundred hours writing GadMget instead.   dB^)

GadMget will parse an Aminet-style file listing (such as the RECENT or INDEX 
files) and allow you to select which files you want by clicking on them in a 
ListView gadget.  After you are done, it will @{"output" link output} the proper mget line(s) 
needed to download your chosen files.

@endnode


@node UsingGadMget "Using GadMget"
  
   @{"The GUI" link GUI}             Where do I click?

   @{"Startup options" link Startup}     Command line arguments & ToolTypes

   @{"File loading" link FileLoading}        Ways of selecting a file to browse

   @{"Menu options" link Menus}        Explanation of cryptic menus

   @{"Keyboard Shortcuts" link Keys}  For people to lazy to use the mouse

   @{"Serving Suggestion" link ServingSuggestion}  Hints
   
@endnode

@node Keys

There are many keyboard equivalents available in GadMget; those that 
correspond to menu items are listed in the menus.  Other keyboard
commands are as follows:

  Up-Arrow         : moves one line up the Available Files List
  Down-Arrow       : moves one line down the Available Files List
  Left-Arrow       : moves one line up the Selected Files List
  Right-Arrow      : moves one line down the Selected Files List

You can modify these keystrokes with the following command keys:

  Shift            : move one ListView's height up or down the list
  Control          : move ten items up or down the list
  Alt              : move to the top or the bottom of the list
  
Also, the backspace key is equivalent to Shift-Up-Arrow, and the Spacebar
is equivalent to Shift-Down-Arrow.

@endnode

@node FileLoading

There are four ways to load a file into GadMget.

The first is to specify the @{"FILE" link FileArg} on the command line or ToolType.

The second is to extend-select the file--that is, hold down the shift key, 
click on the text file's icon once, and then double-click the GadMget icon.

The third method is applicable only when GadMget is open on the @{"Workbench" link Wbscreenarg}
screen.  Here, GadMget is an AppWindow--you may drag the text file's icon into 
the GadMget window, and this will cause GadMget to try to load that file.

The final method is the obvious one--use the bleedin' file requester.  ;-) 

@endnode


@node GUI "The GadMget GUI"

Once the program is started, you will be presented with a screen containing
two ListView gadgets.  The one on the top will contain the contents of
the text file, and the one on bottom will be empty.  Clicking on an item
in the @{"top ListView" link SelectableFiles} will "select" it, moving it to the bottom ListView.
Clicking on an item in the @{"bottom ListView" link SelectedFiles} will send it back.  When you
are done selecting, click the close box or select "Output & Quit", and GadMget
will spit out the @{"output" link output}.  

In the titlebar of the window are several figures about the selected
files.  They should be self-explanatory.
@endnode

@node ServingSuggestion "Serving Suggestion"

Of course, having GadMget put text to your command line isn't very
helpful, what you want is to have the @{"output" link output} go into your ftp program.
One way to work it is to use Jukka Marin's CLIP: device (available on 
Aminet as util/misc/cliphandler.lha) to store the @{"output" link output}.
To do this, type:

GadMget work:RECENT OUTPUT CLIP:

And then after you've quit GadMget, a simple right-amiga-V spits the 
mget commands into your ftp window/Terminus session/whatever.

If you regularly use ncftp to connect to one Aminet ftp site, then
an easier method is available to you.  Simply rx the included AutoFTP
@{"script" link AutoFTP} that is included in this archive, and it will do all the
work for you.  Note that you will probably have to modify this 
script a bit to reflect your directory setup and ftp site of choice,
but it's nothing too difficult if you have a little skill with
AmigaDos.

@endnode


@node Startup "Starting GadMget"

GadMget can be started from either the Shell or the WorkBench.  It supports 
quite a few command line arguments.  Each of these arguments also has a 
ToolType equivalent.  Look in the GadMget icon for examples of these 
ToolTypes--they are there, just commented out with parentheses.

Template:  GadMget FILE/A, OUTPUT/K, LINELENGTH/K, TOP/K, LEFT/K, WIDTH/K, 
                   HEIGHT/K, PUBSCREEN/K, WBSCREEN/S, DEFPUBSCREEN/S, 
                   NOFILES/S, GETREADMES/S, NOPARSE/S, CASESENSITIVE/S,
                   SORTCASESENSITIVE/S, SEARCHCASESENSITIVE/S, NOCOMMAND/S, 
                   NOSPLIT/S, NOAPPWINDOW/S, COMMAND/K, NOSIMPLEPATHS/S, 
                   NOCD/S, HEADER/K, FOOTER/K, FONT/K, FONTSIZE/K, 
                   KEEPBLANKLINES/S, FILESORT/K, GETSORT/K, KEEPFILESORT/S, 
                   KEEPGETSORT/S, AMINETPATH/K, EOL/K, COMMENTCHAR/K,
                   OMITCOMMENTS/S, LOADBUFFERS/K, CLOSEACTION/K

   @{"AMINETPATH/K" link AminetPathArg}           Specify user-defined substitute for ../../
   @{"CASESENSITIVE/S" link CaseSensitiveArg}        Makes sorts AND searches case sensitive
   @{"CLOSEACTION/K" link CloseActionArg}          Specify what to do when window is closed
   @{"COMMAND/K" link CommandArg}              Change output's "mget" to something else
   @{"COMMENTCHAR/K" link CommentCharArg}          Specify the character that denotes a comment
   @{"DEFPUBSCREEN/S" link DefpubscreenArg}         Open on the Default Public Screen
   @{"EOL/K" link EOLArg}                  Specify string to use for End-Of-Line output
   @{"FILE/A" link FileArg}                 File to browse
   @{"FILEPAT/K" link FilePatArg}              Specify default file pattern for ASL requesters
   @{"FILESORT/K" link FilesortArg}             Specify default File ListView sort
   @{"FONT/K" link FontArg}                 Specify font to use
   @{"FONTSIZE/K" link FontsizeArg}             Specify font size to use
   @{"FOOTER/S" link FootArg}               Textfile to postpend to output
   @{"GETREADMES/S" link GetreadmesArg}           Generate .readme files 
   @{"GETSORT/K" link GetSortArg}              Specify default Get ListView sort
   @{"HEADER/S" link HeadArg}               Textfile to prepend to output
   @{"HEIGHT/K" link HeightArg}               Window height
   @{"KEEPBLANKLINES/S" link Keepblanklines}       Display empty lines (day separators)
   @{"KEEPFILESORT/S" link KeepFileSortArg}         Default to keeping File ListView sorted
   @{"KEEPGETSORT/S" link KeepGetSortArg}          Default to keeping Get ListView sorted
   @{"LEFT/K" link LeftArg}                 Window x co-ordinate
   @{"LINELENGTH/K" link LinelengthArg}           Maximum output line length
   @{"LOADBUFFERS/K" link LoadBuffersArg}          Specify size of load buffer
   @{"NOAPPWINDOW/S" link NoappwindowArg}          Disable AppWindow
   @{"NOCD/S"   link nocdArg}                 Don't output CD commands
   @{"NOCOMMAND/S" link NoCommandArg}            Don't generate "mget " 
   @{"NOFILES/S" link NofilesArg}              Don't generate archive names 
   @{"NOPARSE/S" link NoparseArg}              Don't parse output, just print raw data
   @{"NOSIMPLEPATHS/S" link Output}        Don't use pathless output style
   @{"NOSPLIT/S" link NosplitArg}              Don't generate multiple mget commands
   @{"OMITCOMMENTS/S" link OmitCommentArg}         Don't load comment lines
   @{"OUTPUT/K" link OutputArg}               Where to send the output
   @{"PUBSCREEN/K" link PubscreenArg}            Open on a Public Screen
   @{"SEARCHCASESENSITIVE/S" link SearchCaseSensitiveArg}  Makes searches case sensitive
   @{"SORTCASESENSITIVE/S" link SortCaseSensitiveArg}    Makes sorts case sensitive
   @{"TOP/K" link TopArg}                  Window y co-ordinate
   @{"WBSCREEN/S" link WbscreenArg}             Open on the Workbench Screen
   @{"WIDTH/K" link WidthArg}                Window width
@endnode

@node CloseActionArg

In the past, GadMget has always automatically spit out output for
the selected lines, whenever the GadMget window was closed.  Now,
however, this behavior can be modified.  If you wish GadMget to
save the state of the current file, instead, you can specify it
as follows:

Usage Example:  GadMget CLOSEACTION save

Or if you prefer that GadMget do nothing when the window is closed:

Usage Example:  GadMget CLOSEACTION quit

or, a synonym:

Usage Example:  GadMget CLOSEACTION none

If you wish GadMGet to both save _and_ output, try this:

Usage Example:  GadMget CLOSEACTION saveoutput

And, for completeness (although it's the default anyway)

Usage Example:  GadMget CLOSEACTION output

@endnode

@node LoadBuffersArg

By specifying this keyword you can control the number of kilobytes of
memory used by the file loading buffering algorithm.  The higher the 
number you specify is, the faster things will load, but the
more memory will be used (temporarily) while the file is loading.

If GadMget cannot allocate enough memory for the buffer, it will try
again using a buffer that is ten times smaller, until the allocation
succeeds, or the buffer becomes less than 1k.

Here are some rough timings I made for loading ftp.netnet.net's INDEX
file on my A3000/25's Maxtor:

   				    Using FastCache	Without FastCache
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
 No buffers (GadMget v1.97)               20 sec.             25 sec.
  1K buffer                               17 sec.             21 sec.
 30K buffer                               14 sec.             15 sec.
300K buffer                               13 sec.             13 sec.

As you can see, there is a point at which a bigger buffer does not buy 
you any more speed--I tried a 3000K (!) buffer, and got results that were 
the same or slower than the 300K results.

The default value is 30K, and you can lower it as low as 1K or raise
it as high as you can afford memory for.  (Make sure that you have
memory to hold both the buffer and the list you're loading in at once,
otherwise GadMget will abort the load!)

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent LOADBUFFERS 30

@endnode

@node OmitCommentArg

Specifying this switch will cause GadMget to suppress any lines
beginning with the @{"Comment Character" link CommentCharArg}.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent OMITCOMMENTS

@endnode

@node CommentCharArg

With this argument you can change the character that GadMget uses
to recognize a comment.  Any string that starts with the Comment
character will not be sorted, and if the @{"OMITCOMMENTS" link OmitCommentArg} argument
is specified, they will not be displayed either.

The default comment character is "|".  The comment character must
be the first character in a line to be recognized.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent COMMENTCHAR %

@endnode


@node FilePatArg

With this argument you can specify a string to appear by default
as the pattern matching string in the ASL file requesters.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent FILEPAT REC#?.TXT

@endnode

@node EOLArg

This argument allows you to specify a different string besides "\r\n"
(carriage return, newline) for GadMget to print at the end of each line
of output.  This can be any string less than 50 characters long, and
\r will be interpreted as a carriage return, \n as a newline, and \\ as
a single backslash.  Other characters and backslash combinations will
be output verbatim.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent EOL "\n"

@endnode


@node AminetPathArg

This argument allows you to specify another string besides "../../"
for GadMget to use when CD'ing to a new directory.  

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent AMINETPATH "/pub/aminet/"

Will cause GadMget to use absolute directory names.

@endnode

@node KeepFileSortArg

This argument causes GadMget to default to keeping the @{"Files ListView" link SelectableFiles} sorted.

NOTE:  Specifying this function can make Selects and Deselects rather slow when
       working with long lists (e.g. INDEX).  Use with care.
       
Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent KEEPFILESORT

@endnode

@node KeepGetSortArg

This argument causes GadMget to default to keeping the @{"Get ListView" link SelectedFiles} sorted.

NOTE:  Specifying this function can make Selects and Deselects rather slow when
       working with long lists (e.g. INDEX).  Use with care.
      
Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent KEEPGETSORT

@endnode

@node FileSortArg

This argument allows you to specify one of the four sort methods to be
used by default in the @{"Files (top) ListView" link SelectableFiles}.  The keyword for the filetype
you prefer should be written after this keyword (or after the = if you are
setting this option in ToolTypes)

The four sort type keywords are:  Size, Description, FileName, and Directory.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent FILESORT FileName

@endnode

@node GetSortArg

This argument allows you to specify one of the four sort methods to be
used by default in the @{"Get (bottom) ListView" link SelectedFiles}.  The keyword for the filetype
you prefer should be written after this keyword (or after the = if you are
setting this option in ToolTypes)

The four sort type keywords are:  Size, Description, Filename, and Directory.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent GETSORT Size

@endnode



@node Keepblanklines

If specified, this switch will prevent GadMget from suppressing the
display (and printout, if Aminet parse is disabled) of blank lines
in the input file.

@endnode

@node FontArg

This argument lets you specify your favorite font to use in GadMget.
The argument is case insensitive, and the .font extension is optional.
If this argument is not specified, or the font is not found, GadMget
will use the System Default Font (if run from WorkBench) or Topaz 8
(if run from the CLI).

Note:  Using a proportional font is going to make things look messy!

@endnode

@node FontSizeArg

This argument allows you to specify the size of the font you want to
use.  If a Font is specified and this argument isn't, a size of 12
will be used.  If the font size specified does not exist, the font
will be algorithmically scaled to the specified size (warning: ugly!).

@endnode

@node HeadArg

This argument allows you to specify a textfile for GadMget to output just
before it outputs the directory data.  

Shell Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent HEADER s:GadMget.header

Why is this useful?  Well, I use it with the following file:

---(snip)---
cd pub/aminet
binary
hash
---(snip)---

to automatically do the (tedious) setup commands before I download.

@endnode


@node FootArg

This argument allows you to specify a textfile for GadMget to output just
after it outputs the directory data.

Shell Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent FOOTER s:GadMget.footer

This argument is implemented mostly just to be symmetric with the HEADER
argument--although you might want to put in a "cd ../.." or a "quit" command
in the text file.

@endnode

@node nocdArg

This argument allows you to suppress the cd commands output by GadMget when
@{"Simple Path Mode" link Output} is selected.  It has no effect if Simple
Path Mode is not selected.

Shell Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent NOCD

@endnode

@node CommandArg

This argument allows you to change the command GadMget prepends to the
filelist.  

Note that GadMget does not automatically put a space between the 
command you specify and the filepath, you should do this yourself
if you want.  (see the example, below)

Shell Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent COMMAND "sz "

This would cause GadMget to create output lines like this:

cd biz/dbase
sz dfa-21.lha 
cd ../../comm/term
sz term-4.0-DVI.lha term-4.0-030.lha 
cd ../../dev/asm
sz BarflyDemo.lha GEDindent.lha memleak.lha 
cd ../../docs/misc
sz C_Tutor.lha 

@endnode


@node NoappwindowArg

Specifying this argument will turn off GadMget's ability to load new files
via the @{"AppWindow" link AppWindow} mechanism.  This argument only takes
effect if GadMget is running on the WorkBench screen.

@endnode

@node AppWindow

When run on the WorkBench screen, GadMget's window is an AppWindow.  What
this means is, you may load a new file into GadMget's @{"top ListView" link SelectableFiles} gadget
by dragging their icons into the window.

The effect is exactly the same as if you had selected "Open" from the Project
Menu and selected that file.

@endnode

@node OutputArg

This argument tells GadMget where to send its output string.  If this
argument is not specified, and GadMget is started from the shell, the
output will be sent to stdout.  If the argument is not specified and
GadMget is started from the Workbench, output will be send to the file
"RAM:GadMget.output".

Shell Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent OUTPUT ram:MyTempFile.txt

@endnode

@node SelectedFiles "The Lower Gadget - Selected Files"

The lower of the two ListView gadgets displays a list of all of the files you 
have selected to output.  If you click on a line of text in this gadget, it 
will be transported back up to the @{"Selectable Files" link SelectableFiles} 
gadget and put at the end of the Selectable Files list.

@endnode

@node SelectableFiles "The Upper Gadget - Selectable Files"

The upper of the two ListView gadgets displays a list of all the files in
the file listing you have selected to browse.  Clicking on any of these
files will put it in the @{"Selected Files" link SelectedFiles} gadget near
the bottom of the window, thus indicating that you want to output the name
of that file in the mget line.

There are certain lines that GadMget will not allow you to transport to
the lower ListView.  Lines that GadMget does not think are archive listing
lines will not move, and if @{"Get Files" link GetFilesGad} is not selected,
you will not be able to selected lines that do not contain a @{"plus" link plus} symbol
after the file size.

@endnode


@node NosplitArg "Disable Command-Splitting"

This argument deactivates the @{"Split Commands" link SplitcommandsGad} gadget 
in the @{"Output menu" link OutputMenu}.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent NOSPLIT

@endnode


@node NoCommandArg "Suppress mget printing"

This argument causes GadMget to never generate the command "mget" at the
beginning of its @{"output" link output} lines.  With this keyword, you can generate just
a pure list of files, should you need one.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent NOCOMMAND

@endnode


@node CaseSensitiveArg "Case Sensitivity"

Specifying this argument has the same effect as specifying both
@{"SEARCHCASESENSITIVE" link searchcasesensitivearg} and @{"SORTCASESENSITIVE" link sortcasesensitivearg}.  It is included for
convenience.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent CASESENSITIVE

@endnode

@node SearchCaseSensitiveArg "Case Sensitivity"

This argument activates the "Case Sensitive" menu item
in the @{"Find menu" link Findmenu}.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent SEARCHCASESENSITIVE

@endnode

@node SortCaseSensitiveArg "Case Sensitivity"

This argument activates the "Case Sensitive" menu item
in the @{"Sort menu" link Sortmenu}.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent SORTCASESENSITIVE

@endnode

@node NoparseArg "Aminet Style Parsing"

This argument deactivates the @{"Aminet Parse" link AminetparseGad} menu item
in the @{"Output menu" link OutputMenu}.

Usage example:  GadMget work:recent NOPARSE
 
@endnode 

@node GetreadmesArg "Grabbing .readme files"

This argument activates the @{"Get Readmes" link GetReadmesGad} menu item
in the @{"Output menu" link OutputMenu}.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent GETREADMES

@endnode

@node NofilesArg "Grabbing archive files"

This argument deactivates the @{"Get Files" link GetFilesGad link } menu item
in the @{"Output menu" link OutputMenu }.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent NOFILES

@endnode

@node DefpubscreenArg "Default Public Screen"

This keyword causes GadMget to appear on the default Public Screen.

Note that this may cause GadMget to appear on the Workbench screen, if
the Workbench screen is the default Public Screen.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent DEFPUBSCREEN

@endnode


@node WbscreenArg "Workbench Screen"

This keyword causes GadMget to appear on the Workbench Screen.

Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent WBSCREEN

@endnode



@node PubscreenArg "Specify a Public Screen"

This allows you to specify the name of a Public Screen upon which you want
the GadMget window to appear.  If a Public Screen with the given name does
not exist, GadMget will fail with a "Couldn't lock public screen!" error.

Remember, with Public Screen names, alphabetical case counts!

Usage Example:

GadMget work:recent PUBSCREEN MyPubScreen24

@endnode




@node HeightArg "Specify window height"

This allows you to set the height of the GadMget window.

Usage Example:

GadMget work:recent HEIGHT 250

will make the GadMget window 250 pixels tall.

The height of the window cannot be less than 167 pixels.

@endnode


@node WidthArg "Specify Window width"

This allows you to set the width of the GadMget window.

Usage Example:

GadMget work:recent WIDTH 350

will make the GadMget window 350 pixels wide.

The width of the window cannot be less than 155 pixels.

@endnode


@node LeftArg "Specify window X-coordinate"

This allows you to set the horizontal position of the GadMget window.

Usage Example:

GadMget work:recent LEFT 60

will make the GadMget window appear 60 pixels from the left of the screen.

@endnode



@node TopArg "Specify window Y-coordinate"

This allows you to set the vertical position of the GadMget window.

Usage Example:

GadMget work:recent TOP 60 

will make the GadMget window appear 60 pixels from the top of the screen.


@endnode



@node LinelengthArg "Line length"

The Amiga shell and possibly other programs will truncate commands that are
over a certain number of characters long.  The Amiga shell's maximum command
length size is 255 characters, for instance.  With this in mind, GadMget will
generate multiple commands, none of which are longer than this value.  If you
wish to change this value, you may do so via the command line keyword 
LINELENGTH or via the "Line Length..." item in the @{"Output Menu" link OutputMenu}.

Setting this value to 1 will cause GadMget to never put more than one
file on a single command line.

Shell Usage Example:

GadMget work:recent LINELENGTH 150

@endnode



@node FileArg "FILE/A"

GadMget will look for this keyword in your command string, and try to load
the file specified directly after it.  If it cannot find this keyword, it
will try use the first argument on the command line as its file to load.
(Even if the first word is a parameter as well!)

Shell Usage Example:  GadMget work:recent
Shell Usage Example:  GadMget WBSCREEN WIDTH 50 FILE work:recent

@endnode

@node Menus "GadMget menus"

  GadMget has a few menus for you to play with...
  
  
   @{"Project" link ProjectMenu}   - The regular stuff

   @{"Find" link FindMenu}      - Searching for text in the list

   @{"Sort" link SortMenu}      - Sort either of the ListViews

   @{"Output" link OutputMenu}    - Output format control
   
@endnode

@node SortMenu "Sort Menu"

This menu is disabled if Aminet Parse is disabled, since most operations
will not make sense if GadMget cannot interpret the lists as Aminet lists.

The first two submenus, "Files List" and "Get List" pertain to the Lists
in the Upper and Lower ListViews, respectively.  They both have the same
form, which is:

By Directory   - Sorts the files by their directory pathnames.  This is a 
                 good way to keep your output sorted if you want to generate
                 as few "cd" commands as possible in the output.  (Note:
                 if do not you have @{"Simple Paths" link Output} selected, sorting
                 your output with this will not lessen the size of the output.

By Size        - Sorts the files by file size, smallest to largest.  This is
                 a good order to select if you like to unpack/view archives while
                 downloading in the background.  This way you can examine lots
                 of little archives first while downloading the big ones.
               
By FileName    - Sorts the files alphabetically by filename.

By Description - Sorts the files alphabetically by description.

By Age         - Sorts the files by age as indicated in the "weeks old" 
                 column.  You must, of course, be using RECENT/INDEX files
                 with this column in them for this to work properly.
                 
Keep Sorted    - If this is checked, GadMget will try to keep the appropriate
                 list sorted to whichever sort format you last specified.  If
                 you never selected a "sort", GadMget will default to "sort by
                 directory".  Note that using this option can make Selecting
                 and Deselecting items rather slow when working with large
                 lists (e.g. INDEX)


The Sort Menu contains two other items as well:


Sort Algorithm - This SubMenu allows you to choose between the two available
                 methods of sorting the Lists.  The default, "Tree Sort", is
                 very quick, but will need to allocate additional memory in
                 order to perform the sort.  The amount of memory the Tree
                 Sort will use depends on how long the List being sorted is--
                 For the entire Aminet INDEX list, it needs about 324k.
                 This sort will take rougly the same amount of time regardless
                 of how close to being sorted the list was to begin with.
                 
                 The other method, "Bubble Sort", is very primitive--it
                 simply goes through the list and switches every out-of-order
                 pair of items it finds, until there it can find no more
                 out of order pairs.  This requires no additional memory,
                 but it can take a LONG LONG time if the list wasn't already
                 close to being sorted.  Use with care!  (Or better yet, 
                 don't use it at all!)
                 
Case Sensitive - This toggle allows you to indicate whether or not you want
                 GadMget to take Upper/Lower case into account when sorting.
                 For example, Case Sensitive is not selected, then "Amiga.lha"
                 would be listed next to "amiga.lha".
             
            
@endnode

               
@node ProjectMenu "Project Menu"

Open    - Brings up the lovely and talented ASL filerequester to allow you to
          select a new file to load in.  Only the @{"Selectable Files" link SelectableFiles} 
          gadget will be affected.

Append  - Same as Open, only it puts the new file at the end of the old one,
          without first clearing the old stuff.

Save    - Allows you to save the current state of the program back to the
	  file currently being edited.  The lists will be re-written out
	  to the input file in the currently displayed order, and a special
	  "bookmark" line will be inserted so that next time, GadMget will
	  know which lines you had selected.

Save As - Same as Save, but you are prompted for a file to save to.

Clear   - This is a submenu with two items.  The first will clear the Files 
          ListView (the upper one), and the second will clear the Get ListView
          (the lower one).
          
About   - Opens a leetle info-window about @{"me" link Me} and the program.
 
Iconify - Makes GadMget reduce itself to an icon on the Workbench.  You can
          then double-click on this icon to resume using GadMget, or drag
          icons onto it to load them into GadMget.  (Note:  GadMget gets
          its AppIcon from the icon that goes with the GadMget executable.
          This means you can replace it with your own by replacing GadMGet's
          program icon, if you wish.  It also means that it's a good idea
          to keep GadMget's icon with the executable.)

Output & Quit - Makes GadMget spit out its @{"output" link output} and go away.
		Selecting this is equivalent to clicking the close gadget.

Save & Quit - Causes GadMget to save the current contents of the two ListViews
	      out to the current input file, and then quit without generating
	      any output.  Useful for when you want to remember your selections,
	      but don't want to download them right now.

Quit    - Makes GadMget quit without taking any other action.

@endnode

@node FindMenu "Find Menu"

Find Forward      - Opens a window to allow searches of the @{"Selectable Files" link SelectableFiles}
                    gadget for any text string.  All searches initiated with 
                    this menu item will start from the first currently visible
                    item in the ListView.

Find Backward     - Opens a window to allow searches of the @{"Selectable Files" link SelectableFiles}
                    gadget for any text string.  All searches initiated with 
                    this menu item will start from the first currently visible
                    item in the ListView and proceed backwards towards the top
                    of the List.

Find from Top     - Opens a window to allow searches of the @{"Selectable Files" link SelectableFiles}
                    gadget for any text string.  All searches initiated with 
                    this menu item will start from the top of the list.
                 
Find from Bottom  - Opens a window to allow searches of the @{"Selectable Files" link SelectableFiles}
                    gadget for any text string.  All searches initiated with 
                    this menu item will start from the bottom of the list and
                    go backwards.
                   
Find Next         - Use this after having found an item with Find.  This will
                    find the next line that contains the same text string.

Find Previous     - Works like "Find Next", only searches backwards.

Find Current      - Returns to the last item that was highlighted by any
                    Find function.  Good for when you "lose your place".
                    
Select Multiple   - This item will prompt you to enter a key string, and will
                    then transfer every item in the @{"Selectable Files" link selectablefiles} list that
                    contains that key string to the @{"Selected Files" link selectedfiles} list.
                    If you enter an empty string into the gadget, no action
                    will be taken.  Note that a string of spaces is NOT an
                    empty string!
                   
                    Multiple Select is a very powerful command!  For example, 
                    to download every module (music) file on Aminet, you 
                    could open the INDEX to your ftp site and do a Multiple 
                    Select on "mods/".  Or to download all 18,000+ files 
                    (about 2.6 Gigabytes!), you could do a select on "/".  
                    Be careful!
                    
Deselect Multiple - This item will prompt you to enter a key string, and will
                    then transfer every item in the @{"Selected Files" link selectedfiles} list that
                    contains that key string to the @{"Selectable Files" link selectablefiles} list.
                    If you enter an empty string into the gadget, no action
                    will be taken.  Note that a string of spaces is NOT an
                    empty string!

Case Sensitive    - Decides whether or not alphabetical case matters in a 
                    search or (de)select.  (i.e. is "Amiga" the same 
                    as "amiga"?)
@endnode

@node LinelengthGad "Specify Line Length"

This allows you to change the maximum length of the @{"output" link output} lines
that GadMget will produce.  The default is 255 characters, the maximum amount
that the Amiga shell can handle on one line.

@endnode
@node OutputMenu "Output Menu"

This menu controls the formatting of the text output that GadMget generates.

@{"Aminet Parse" link AminetparseGad}     - Toggles Aminet listing -> filepath parsing

@{"Get Files" link GetfilesGad}        - If set, GadMget will get the archives that are selected

@{"Get Readmes" link GetreadmesGad}      - If set, GadMget will get the .readme files associated 
                   with the selected archives.

@{"Split Commands" link SplitcommandsGad}   - If set, GadMget will generate multiple "mget" lines.

@{"Use Simple Paths" link Output} - If set, GadMget will output Simple Path style commands

@{"Line Length" link LinelengthGad}      - Allows you to set the maximum output line length

@{"Output Now" link OutputNow}       - Outputs without quitting program

@{"Output To..." link OutputTo}     - Change output destination

@endnode

@node OutputNow

Selecting this causes GadMget to spit out its output immediately, without
having to quit.  This is useful if you want the same or similar lists
output to several files.

@endnode

@node OutputTo

This brings up a string requester, into which you can type a filepath/filename
or device name that you want GadMget to output to.  Note that this does not
cause GadMget to actually output anything, it just changes the output 
destination for when it does output.

@endnode

@node SplitcommandsGad "Use Command Splitting"

The Amiga shell (and doubtless many other programs) can only handle line 
lengths up to a certain size (255 characters to be exact).  Because of this,
when there are more than a few files selected for output, GadMget must split
its output into multiple "mget" commands.

If you wish to deactivate this command-splitting mechanism, then deselect
"Split Commands".  Note that this will deactivate the @{"Line Length" link LinelengthGad} menu
item, since it is meaningless unless you want to split commands.

@endnode



@node AminetparseGad "Use Aminet-Style Parsing"

Normally this program is to be used in conjunction with FTP and the Aminet
FTP sites to generate mget command lines.  To generate command lines properly,
GadMget has to make assumptions sucha as where in each line of text the file
name and path are going to be.

However, it may be that you want to use GadMget without Aminet in mind,
perhaps from a script to allow the user to select a sublist of some other 
list.

If that is the case, you can turn Aminet Parse off and GadMget will simply
echo the selected lines to the output file, verbatim.

Note that because most of the other options in the Output menu are related
to Aminet-style parsing, de-selecting Aminet Parse will disable them.

@endnode

@node GetfilesGad "Grab archive files"

Usually you will want to download the archives that you select in GadMget,
but sometimes (perhaps over a slow modem?) you might want to get just the
.readme files.  If this is the case, deselect Get Files to tell GadMget
that you don't want the archives.

Deselecting Get Files will automatically select @{"Get Readmes"GetreadmesGad}, since if neither 
was selected, you wouldn't be able to get anything.

Note that when Get Files is deselected, you will not be able to select any
files that do not have a @{"'+' symbol" link plus} directly after the file size.  The
'+' means that there is an .readme to go with that archive, and so if 
there is no plus there is no .readme, and if there is no .readme, then
you can't get it.  So there ;)

Any lines without readmes that you have already selected will remain in the
@{"Selected Files" link SelectedFiles} gadget, but they will not be output.

@endnode

@node plus "What the plus symbol means"

In an Aminet listing, for any line where there is a + after the file size,
there is an accompanying .readme file to go along with the archive.  GadMget
will automatically get this .readme file for you if you have the @{"Get Readmes" link GetreadmesGad}
option selected

@endnode

@node GetReadmesGad "Grab .readme files"

Select this menu item if you want to get the @{".readme files" link plus} that are included
with many of the archives on Aminet.  

Deselecting this menu item will cause @{"Get Files" link GetfilesGad} to be automatically selected,
since if neither was selected, you wouldn't be able to get anything.

@endnode



